Escape from Shenzhen complete, and wee Evy met a friend at the train station while we waited with the masses to catch a ride back to Guangzhou. Now safe and sound back home, pondering the lessons of this past weekend: 1) I've missed live hockey, it's a good time; 2) paying Â¥200 for fish and chips is just too much; and 3) after years of false alerts and drizzly typhoons, I've learned that a red typhoon warning can result in pretty serious real-world consequences. This last one may sound silly, but the last time I recall a red typhoon warning in Guangzhou the storm never showed up and we had a sunny, rain-free day off work.

Waves and wind have died down. Typhoon Mangkhut has passed. Whoever's job it is to get all that sand out of the hotel swimming pool (aka that trash-strewn pond below) is not someone I envy.

Say what you will about getting excited over Western cuisine in a foodie haven like Canton, but Mr. Chef Rob from the LN Garden Hotel is killing it. 
1. Canadian scallops with lemongrass foam, kaffir lime meringue and tempura basil. 
2. Beef carpaccio with pickled cucumbers, Yunnan mushrooms and lemon aioli.
3. Dupont oysters with Alaskan king crab meat, feta, capers and herb garlic dressing. 
4. Wagyu boneless short ribs with baby carrots, roasted garlic and Bourbon gravy. 
5. Velvety cheese cake with passion fruit curd, fresh mango and pistachios.

There is nothing like fresh Xinjiang 'nang' flatbread early in the morning, particularly when it's straight out of the wood-burning brick oven. This staple food of Uyghur cuisine is made using sesame seeds, butter, veg oil, seeds, milk, salt, sugar and flour. Dip it in tangy Xinjiang yogurt. That, my friends, is the bomb.

The fabled McDonald's 'Szechuan Sauce,' made famous by the hit TV show 'Rick and Morty' is now available in China, alongside a Kung Pao dipping sauce. The Szechuan dip was originally released to help promote the Disney film Mulan and was discontinued in 1998. Twenty years later, it's back!

Some of the best dim sum I've ever had, courtesy of the crack culinary team at Ming Court, in the Langham Place Guangzhou. 1) minced shrimp in giant grouper; 2) shrimp cheungfun; 3) wok-fried beef with homemade black garlic; 4) the almighty xiaolongbao; 5) turnip cake with XO sauce; 6) seasonal veggies; 7) lobster bisque; and 8) white wine jelly with lychee wine pudding and strawberries!
